Excellent service AND sushi. BYOB. We have lived in Roger’s Park since April 1st and have tried so many places from Evanston to Edgewater in search of that perfect neighborhood spot. We found it. The service left nothing to be desired, the French fry appetizer was delicious, and the sushi was of excellent quality. We cannot wait to go back. Check their website for specials! They offer specials every day of the week!

Nori Sushi At Edgewater has been one of our favorite restaurants.  The Asia fusion flavor is so on point.  The Seabass is a must try and the home made desserts are yummy.  Try the mango tapioca which is so light and refreshing.  The pork chops are amazing too.

Nori is the best! Their sushi is phenomenal. 50% off Nori Maki everyday for lunch and all day on Monday. I think it’s a great value for the quality. The service is speedy enough to sit and grab lunch without feeling like your entire day is being taken up. I visit weekly! Favorites are the sweet potato roll, ninja, crunchy spicy tuna, and Mexican maki! Also, try the banana roll for dessert! That’s also amazing.

Been here twice on date night. Atmosphere is nice and low key. Although lighting could be a little less harsh. The Panang Curry is lovely and warm. The sushi is spot on. I'm impressed with their not-peanut sauce for their spring roll appetizer. The Yakisoba is very good. The Garlic Fried Rice has a really nice flavor balance. Service is good and food is ready quickly and accurately. Overall, a definite repeat for someone who doesn't eat out often and is pretty picky about where I spend my money.

The food is good at a reasonable price. However, the server that was attending my table did something so AWKWARD! This is a fascinating place. It's a cozy restaurant with stylish Japanese decor, and chill Brazilian music? So the food... We went for sushi, so that's all I can judge. Nori seems to specialize in rolls, and they do it well. Every one was delicious, beautiful, and made with care. Unfortunately like most sushi restaurants in Chicago, fresh salt water fish is very difficult to come by. Nori is no different. My recommendation is to pass on the nigiri sushi, and focus on the rolls. That's where Nori's artistry shines.
